    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>April 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1878</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I have been very glad to read your essay, &amp; am much obliged to you for sending me the Journal &amp; for promising me a separate copy.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> The Journal is returned by the same post. I think that I have before said how important it seems to me that the notion about the small antiquity of the earth, now so commonly prevailing beyond the pale of working geologists, should be upset.—</p>
<p>Believe me | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            

            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.2 for] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.3 the] <hi rend="italic">over illeg</hi> </note>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">In April 1878, Reade published a paper in the <hi rend="italic">Geological Magazine</hi> titled ‘The age of the world as viewed by the geologist and the mathematician’ (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9610.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Reade 1878</ref>). See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11365.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. M. Reade, 18 February 1878</ref> and n. 2.</note>
        </div>
    
